  "preFix": {
    "title": "Roast duck with orange",
    "subtitle": "Rendered skin, bitter orange pan sauce",
    "excerpt": "A whole duck roasted until the skin is amber and crisp, served with a sharp orange sauce built from the pan drippings. The classic combination since French influence entered British cookery.",
    "sourceNotes": "Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136. Roast duck with bigarade sauce.\n\nEliza Acton, Modern Cookery for Private Families (1845). Roast duck and orange sauce.",
    "body": {
      "type": "doc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Duck roasting has two goals: rendered, crisp skin and a finished internal temperature above 75 degrees C in the leg. The thick fat layer means it needs longer at a moderate heat than chicken. Pricking the skin before it goes in helps the fat escape.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "What you need",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "ingredientsList",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "name": "Whole duck",
                "unit": "each",
                "amount": 1,
                "prepNote": "about 2 kg, giblets removed",
                "groupLabel": null,
                "isOptional": false,
                "ingredientId": "cmp49f4o90032rkv4e4t9u7fj",
                "ingredientSlug": "duck-whole"
              },
