        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Method",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Prepare and roast the duck",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Heat the oven to 200 degrees C fan. Prick the duck skin all over with a skewer or fork, especially on the thighs and breast, to help the fat render. Season inside and out with salt.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Stuff the cavity loosely with the quartered orange and thyme sprigs. Place the duck breast-side up on a rack in a deep roasting tin. The rack is important: it keeps the duck out of the rendered fat.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Roast for 2 hours, pouring off the rendered fat into a heatproof jug halfway through. The duck skin needs this ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "rendering",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpsoi2480000q8v4hxdripbk"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " time to become crisp. The skin should be amber-brown and the legs should feel loose.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Make the orange sauce",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Transfer the duck to a board to rest. Pour off all but 1 tablespoon of fat from the roasting tin.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Set the tin over medium heat and ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "deglaze",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmp73vlkc0001wwv4i1qpucp8"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " with the port, scraping up any sticky brown bits. Add the orange juice, red wine vinegar, brown sugar, and hot stock. Bring to a simmer and reduce for 5 minutes until slightly syrupy. Strain through a fine-mesh sieve into a warm jug.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "Always use a rack. Prick the skin thoroughly before roasting, especially in the thick areas of the thigh. If still pale, raise the temperature to 220 degrees C for the final 20 minutes.",
                "cause": "The duck was not pricked enough, or was not raised on a rack so it sat in its own fat.",
                "symptom": "The skin is soft and pale even after 2 hours"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Add a splash more red wine vinegar and taste again. The sauce should be sweet-sharp.",
                "cause": "The orange used was sweet-skinned, or too much sugar was added.",
                "symptom": "The sauce tastes too sweet"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Simmer uncovered for a few more minutes. The sauce should lightly coat a spoon.",
                "cause": "Not enough reduction time.",
                "symptom": "The sauce is too thin"
              },
              {
                "fix": "The internal temperature of the thigh should reach 75 degrees C. If the breast is cooked but the legs are not, cover the breast with foil and continue roasting for another 15 minutes.",
                "cause": "The breast cooks faster than the legs. The legs need more time.",
                "symptom": "The leg meat is pink and underdone even when the breast looks cooked"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Variations",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Use blood oranges in winter for a more intense, less sweet sauce. For a simpler version without the sauce, just roast the duck with salt and serve with the natural pan juices. A cherry sauce using the same deglazing method works well in late summer.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Duck with orange sauce entered British cookery from France, where it is known as canard a l'orange or duck bigarade. Victorian cookery writer Mrs Beeton included a version in 1861, calling for the bitter Seville orange. The dish fell in and out of fashion through the twentieth century, became briefly associated with 1970s dinner party excess, and has since settled as a reliable classic.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    "servings": 4,
